    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial and operational highlights, here are the details regarding the Connectivity segment\'s business description, Starlink subscriber growth, and discussions on operating leverage, cost structure, and margin expansion:\n\n### **1. Connectivity Segment Business Description**\nThe Connectivity segment is primarily driven by **Starlink**, which provides global, high-speed, low-latency internet access via a Low-Earth Orbit (LEO) constellation. As of March 31, 2026, the segment operated over 9,600 broadband and mobile satellites. The business is divided into several key offerings:\n*   **Consumer Broadband:** Operates the world’s largest space-based internet service, offering fiber-like download speeds (median 225 Mbps during peak hours) and low latency (~25 milliseconds). While initially focused on rural, remote, and underserved communities, the value proposition is expanding into suburban and urban environments as network capacity grows.\n*   **Enterprise Solutions:** Provides critical primary or backup connectivity to industries such as aviation, maritime, construction, agriculture, retail, telecom, and hospitality. Major customers include United Airlines, Carnival, Maersk, and John Deere. \n*   **Mobile Connectivity:** Offers satellite-to-mobile texting and over-the-top voice services to supplement terrestrial networks and eliminate "dead zones" across approximately 30 countries.\n*   **Revenue Model:** Generates revenue through monthly subscription fees (varying by geography and speed), upfront terminal/kit sales, and enterprise contracts based on subscriptions, data consumption, or capacity.\n\n### **2. Starlink Subscriber Growth**\nStarlink has experienced explosive user adoption, driven by global brand awareness, expanded retail distribution, and new product offerings:\n*   **Subscriber Base:** As of March 31, 2026, Starlink reached approximately **10.3 million subscribers** across 164 countries/territories. This represents a massive **~105% year-over-year growth** from 5.0 million subscribers in Q1 2025 (and up from 2.3 million at the end of 2023).\n*   **Mobile Users:** The satellite-to-mobile service has scaled to approximately **7.4 million monthly unique devices**.\n*   **ARPU Dynamics:** Rapid subscriber growth has been accompanied by a decline in Average Revenue Per User (ARPU). ARPU fell to $66 in Q1 2026 (down 22.9% YoY) and averaged $81 for FY2025 (down 11.2% YoY). This decline is a strategic result of international expansion into emerging markets and the introduction of lower-priced, localized service plans to drive mass adoption.\n\n### **3. Operating Leverage, Cost Structure, and Margin Expansion**\nThe financial highlights demonstrate significant operating leverage and a highly scalable cost structure, though the company continues to invest heavily in next-generation capacity.\n\n**Margin Expansion & Operating Leverage:**\n*   **Outsized Profit Growth:** In FY2025, the Connectivity segment\'s revenue grew by **49.8%** (to $11.38 billion), but its Income from Operations surged by **120.4%** (to $4.42 billion) and Adjusted EBITDA grew by **86.2%** (to $7.16 billion). This divergence between revenue growth and profit growth highlights strong operating leverage.\n*   **Drivers of Leverage:** The company attributes this sequential EBITDA margin expansion to the "scale and efficiency of our LEO satellite constellations and our highly verticalized supply chain." \n\n**Cost Structure Advantages:**\n*   **Minimal Marginal Costs:** Unlike terrestrial networks that require massive incremental capital expenditures to run cables to low-density areas, Starlink’s space-based architecture enables "economically scalable service delivery across these regions with minimal marginal cost."\n*   **Launch & Hardware Depreciation:** A major component of the segment\'s cost of revenue is the depreciation of capitalized launch and satellite costs. However, the company is actively mitigating this through the increased reusability of its Falcon launch vehicles, which has successfully lowered depreciation expenses in the Space segment.\n*   **Operating Expenses:** Cost increases are currently being driven by ground operating costs, customer support, payment processing, freight, warranty costs, and targeted marketing/international expansion costs required to onboard new users.\n\n**Future Cost & Capacity Catalysts (Starship & V3 Satellites):**\n*   The company is heavily funding R&D for the **Starship** launch vehicle and next-generation **V3 satellites** (offering 1 Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite). \n*   A single Starship launch will be capable of deploying up to 60 V3 satellites, representing a **twenty-fold increase** in downlink capacity deployed relative to a standard Falcon 9 launch. This is expected to drastically improve network efficiency, lower the cost-per-bit, and further expand margins as enterprise and urban adoption scales.',
